What a classic! Coding a snake game in C with image animation can be a fun project. Here's a basic outline to get you started. We'll use the SDL (Simple DirectMedia Layer) library for graphics and input handling.

**Prerequisites:**

1. Install SDL library:
	* On Linux: `sudo apt-get install libsdl2-dev` (for Ubuntu-based systems)
	* On macOS: `brew install sdl2`
	* On Windows: Download the SDL development library from the official website and follow the installation instructions
2. Install a C compiler (if you haven't already): `gcc` on Linux/macOS or Visual Studio on Windows

**Code Structure:**

We'll break down the code into several files:

* `snake.c`: main game logic
* `snake.h`: header file for the main game logic
* `graphics.c`: handles graphics and animation
* `graphics.h`: header file for graphics and animation
* `main.c`: entry point for the game

**snake.c (main game logic):**
```c
#include "snake.h"
#include "graphics.h"

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
    // Initialize SDL
    SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO | SDL_INIT_EVENTS);

    // Create a window and render context
    SDL_Window *window = SDL_CreateWindow("Snake Game", SDL_WINDOWPOS_CENTERED, SDL_WINDOWPOS_CENTERED, 640, 480, SDL_WINDOW_SHOWN);
    SDL_Renderer *renderer = SDL_CreateRenderer(window, -1, SDL_RENDERER_ACCELERATED);

    // Initialize game state
    Snake snake;
    snake.head.x = 100;
    snake.head.y = 100;
    snake.body = (SDL_Rect *)malloc(sizeof(SDL_Rect) * 10);
    snake.body_length = 0;

    // Main game loop
    bool running = true;
    while (running) {
        // Handle events
        SDL_Event event;
        while (SDL_PollEvent(&event)) {
            if (event.type == SDL_QUIT) {
                running = false;
            } else if (event.type == SDL_KEYDOWN) {
                switch (event.key.keysym.sym) {
                    case SDLK_UP:
                        snake.direction = UP;
                        break;
                    case SDLK_DOWN:
                        snake.direction = DOWN;
                        break;
                    case SDLK_LEFT:
                        snake.direction = LEFT;
                        break;
                    case SDLK_RIGHT:
                        snake.direction = RIGHT;
                        break;
                }
            }
        }

        // Update game state
        snake.update();

        // Render game state
        graphics_clear(renderer);
        graphics_draw_snake(renderer, &snake);
        graphics_update(renderer);

        // Update screen
        SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);
    }

    // Clean up
    SDL_Quit();
    free(snake.body);
    return 0;
}
```
This code initializes SDL, creates a window and renderer, initializes the game state, and runs the main game loop. In the loop, it handles events, updates the game state, renders the game state, and updates the screen.

**graphics.c (graphics and animation):**
```c
#include "graphics.h"

void graphics_clear(SDL_Renderer *renderer) {
    SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(renderer, 0, 0, 0, 255); // Clear screen with black
    SDL_RenderClear(renderer);
}

void graphics_draw_snake(SDL_Renderer *renderer, Snake *snake) {
    for (int i = 0; i < snake->body_length; i++) {
        SDL_Rect rect = snake->body[i];
        SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(renderer, 255, 255, 0, 255); // Draw snake body with yellow
        SDL_RenderFillRect(renderer, &rect);
    }
}

void graphics_update(SDL_Renderer *renderer) {
    SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);
}
```
These functions handle clearing the screen, drawing the snake body, and updating the screen.

**graphics.h (header file for graphics and animation):**
```c
#ifndef GRAPHICS_H
#define GRAPHICS_H

void graphics_clear(SDL_Renderer *renderer);
void graphics_draw_snake(SDL_Renderer *renderer, Snake *snake);
void graphics_update(SDL_Renderer *renderer);

#endif  // GRAPHICS_H
```
This header file declares the three functions from `graphics.c`.

**snake.h (header file for main game logic):**
```c
